    {
        "content": "<p>No, there isn't a right adjoint (and examples where a right adjoints exist are rather rare).</p>",
        "id": 192143990,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1585433626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's one of those cases where the name came from convenience rather than following the usual most general convention for subobjects. Inclusions are monos in the category of toposes and geometric morphisms, but they don't constitute <em>all</em> monomorphisms. However, they fit into a nice orthogonal (up to equivalence) factorization system with surjections forming the right-hand class, so they're a very nice class of monos to work with, and we take subtopos to mean \"domain of an inclusion into a given topos\"</p>",
        "id": 192144127,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1585433872
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ah... nlab's page \"subtopos\" defines it as having a geometric embedding &gt;.&lt;</p>",
        "id": 192146985,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438562
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>perhaps it's inconsistent usage between the pages</p>",
        "id": 192147009,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>actually no wait wtf it's on the same page</p>",
        "id": 192147083,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/subtopos#sheaves_localization_closure_and_reflection\" title=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/subtopos#sheaves_localization_closure_and_reflection\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/subtopos#sheaves_localization_closure_and_reflection</a></p>",
        "id": 192147086,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438706
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i guess it doesn't say that the subtopoi are in fact the topoi of sheaves, but</p>",
        "id": 192147093,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i thought that was a pretty reasonable interpretation of what it's saying &gt;.&gt;</p>",
        "id": 192147098,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585438758
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Having a right adjoint would mean the inclusion preserves colimits, which is definitely not true!</p>",
        "id": 192147706,
        "sender_full_name": "vikraman",
        "timestamp": 1585439974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah, i think that occurred to me, and then i confused myself <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span></p>",
        "id": 192147803,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585440082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so what the heck is it talking about?</p>",
        "id": 192147811,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585440095
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The inclusion <em>is</em> the right adjoint. Its left adjoint is sheafification, which preserves finite limits, so the inclusion is a geometric morphism. And it's a geometric embedding because it's fully faithful.</p>",
        "id": 192153677,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1585451768
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the direction of the geometric morphism is the direction of the left adjoint, though</p>",
        "id": 192157796,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1585460299
    },
